Benzene undergoes nitration with HNO₃ and H₂SO₄ to form nitrobenzene (Product 1). Nitrobenzene is then brominated with Br₂ and Fe to form meta-bromonitrobenzene (Product 2). This product is reduced with Pd/C under H₂ to form meta-bromoaniline (Product 3). Treatment of meta-bromoaniline with NaNO₂ and HBF₄ leads to diazotization and subsequent Schiemann reaction, replacing the amino group with a fluorine atom to form meta-bromofluorobenzene (Product 4). Finally, heating Product 4 with anisole results in a nucleophilic aromatic substitution where the fluorine atom is replaced by a methoxy group, yielding 3-bromoanisole as the final product (Product 5).

### Final Answer
The final product is \boxed{3-bromoanisole}
